1. Describe the dataset you chose. Why did you choose it? What features does it include? What year is it from? How was it collected? What should we know about this dataset as we read your write-up? (8pts)¶

Dataset: I have chosen the heart disease dataset from Kaggle. The link for the dataset is given below.

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/johnsmith88/heart-disease-dataset

The dataset consists of 14 columns about human age, sex, and different human-body medical readings as well as a column that signifies the presence of heart disease.

Reason for Choice: I chose this dataset because of the following reasons:

  • My interest in Applied Data Science in the Healthcare Industry.

  • In India, there are a lot of doctor-owned private clinics of various specialties - (like cardiologists, general physicians, medicine, nephrologists, and neurologists, etc). These clinics are not financially big enough to afford complicated models available in the market. That being said, they can still use models that have been trained on the dataset of their patient directory (assuming around 1K - 3K per clinic). The estimate of this number is based on the fact that an average private clinic in India might see 5-8 new patients every day. Building a model that is roughly on the same data scale will help me lay a foundation for building a Software Solution for the same.

Features of the dataset:

  1. age (0 == female, 1 == male)
  2. sex
  3. chest pain type (cp: 4 values)
  4. resting blood pressure (trestbps)
  5. serum cholesterol (chol)in mg/dl
  6. fasting blood sugar (fbs) > 120 mg/dl
  7. resting electrocardiographic results (restecg: values 0,1,2)
  8. maximum heart rate achieved (thalach)
  9. exercise induced angina (exang)
  10. oldpeak = ST depression induced by exercise relative to rest
  11. the slope of the peak exercise ST segment (slope)
  12. number of major vessels (0-3) colored by flourosopy (ca)
  13. thal: 0 = normal; 1 = fixed defect; 2 = reversable defect
  14. target: 0 = The "target" field refers to the presence of heart disease in the patient. 0 = no disease and 1 = disease.

Year of Data Collection: 1988

Data Collection Procedure: The dataset has been sourced from four regions of Cleveland, Hungary, Switzerland, and Long Beach V. The initial data collection contained more than 76 columns. After consultation with medical field experts, ML researchers reduced the number of columns to 14 as described above for research and ML study purposes.

Things to Know About the Dataset:

  • The size of the dataset: 1025
  • Skew of the dataset: 499 entries where target = 0 (disease NOT detected); 526 entries where target = 1 (disease detected)
  • The dataset is relatively clean with no NA entries in the dataset.

2. Define a research question. What are you trying to predict? Describe what you’re trying to accomplish (it will differ between Supervised and Unsupervised learning). (4pts)¶

Research Questions to Answer:

  1. Given the subset of 13 independent variables of the dataset, can we accurately predict the presence or absence of a heart condition for a patient?
  2. What are the top 3 independent variables (bodily conditions/readings) that have a strong direct or inverse correlation with the "target" variable?
  3. What is the highest recall score that we can achieve for this classification problem?

In this problem set, I am trying to develop a machine-learning model that will take as input the above-mentioned 13 independent variables and predict the "target" variable (presence or absence of heart disease as output.) The trained model should be able to predict the presence/absence of heart disease with HIGH Accuracy.

Since this is a classification model, I will also try to accomplish a HIGH Recall Score. This is to ensure that the model does not have a high number of False negatives. In the medical industry, models having low recall scores can prove fatal for the patients diagnosed with the help of that model.

3. Why is this algorithm a good way of answering your research question? (4pts)¶

I have chosen the K-Nearest-Neighbours Classifier as the algorithm. I have chosen this algorithm because the problem we are solving is a supervised learning classification problem. The KNN algorithm is one of the classification algorithms that can be easily explained to the stakeholders. When analyzing the performance and correlation between input, output, and data, it is easier to understand the workings of the model. I believe this is one of the important criteria when developing models related to the field of medical science. Blackbox models can negatively impact the study and analysis with unobserved/unregulated bias that might appear in the model.

In short, KNN models give highly competitive results with highly explainable Simplicity.

4b. Running the Model¶

Pipeline preprocessing components:¶

In [18]:
categorical_columns = ['sex', 'cp', 'fbs', 'restecg', 'exang', 'slope', 'ca', 'thal']
categorical_transformer = Pipeline(steps = [
    ('one_hot', OneHotEncoder())
])

numerical_columns = numerical_columns_and_dependent_column[0: -1]
numerical_transformer = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('min_max', MinMaxScaler())
])

column_transformer = ColumnTransformer(transformers = [
    ('categorical', categorical_transformer, categorical_columns),
    ('numerical', numerical_transformer, numerical_columns)
])
In [19]:
X = df.iloc[:, :-1]
y = df.iloc[:, -1]
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, random_state = 3)
In [20]:
scores = []
n_values = []
for n in range(1, 42, 2):
    knn_classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n)
    pipeline = Pipeline(steps = [
        ('column_tansformer', column_transformer),
        ('cross_val_classifier', knn_classifier)
    ])
    score = cross_val_score(pipeline, X_train, y_train, cv=5)
    n_values.append(n)
    scores.append(np.mean(score))
In [21]:
acc_plot = sns.lineplot(x=n_values, y = scores, marker="o")
acc_plot.axvline(x = 5, ymin = 0, ymax = 1, c='limegreen') 
acc_plot.set(xlabel="K-Values", ylabel="Accuracy", title="KNN accuracy over different values of K")
Out[21]:
[Text(0.5, 0, 'K-Values'),
 Text(0, 0.5, 'Accuracy'),
 Text(0.5, 1.0, 'KNN accuracy over different values of K')]

Explanation:¶

We can see that the model performance starts with almost 100% accuracy on the validation set (N=1), and drops to a minimum value at N=5.

This is because the model is overfitting and memorizing all the values in the training set, causing the accuracy score to be very high initially. Because of this, we will not choose any value of n <= 5 (represented by the values left to the green line.

When considering the remaining portion - we will go ahead and choose one of the values with n = 7, 9 and 11 based on feature selection and performance.

SHORT-LISTED N VALUES = [7, 9, 11]

    knn_classifier = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=n)
    pipeline = Pipeline(steps = [
        ('column_tansformer', column_transformer_subset),
        ('cross_val_classifier', knn_classifier)
    ])
    pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_pred = pipeline.predict(X_test)
    acc_scr = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    precision_scr = precision_score(y_test, y_pred)
    recall_scr = recall_score(y_test, y_pred)
    f1_scr = f1_score(y_test, y_pred)

    print(f"Model Performance Metrics for n = {n}    ")

    print(f"Precision Score: {precision_scr}")
    print(f"Recall Score: {recall_scr}")
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1_scr}")
    print("**********************************************\n")

6. Report the evaluation of your model.¶

Based on the analysis done so far, we have three potential models that we can select going forward.

KNN Model with N = 7:`This model has comparatively lower performance when measured across "Accuracy", "Precision" and "F1 Score". The model is tied on performance when measured over "Recall" score.

KNN Model with N = 9:`This model performs slightly better when measured across "Accuracy", "Precision" and "F1 Score" when compared against model with N = 7. Although, its accuracy and precision is slightly weaker than model with N = 11.

KNN Model with N = 11:`This model performs better than N=7 and N=9 when measured across "Accuracy", "Precision". The "F1 score" is similar to model N = 9 and has lower recall score compared to model N = 9.

------------------------------------------------------- OVERALL DECISION --------------------------------------------------------:

I will choose Model with N = 9, because it has the best recall score (0.90816) amongst the three models. As described in Q2, recall score is one of the most important metrics as we want to minimize "False Negative" predictions as in medical condition diagnosis, this can result in high fatality. The model F1_score is (0.8725). The model also has almost equal performance on all other metrics when compared against top performing model (either N = 7 or N = 9 for each parameter respectively).

8. Challenges Encountered¶

  • The main challenge encountered during the design of the solution was no expert consultation to understand the importance of critical features in detecting heart conditions. Although researchers have curated the list to 14 parameters, it was difficult to come up with a list of features to train the model upon. When developing the model further, it will be important to seek medical science expert opinion, especially in feature selection. This would help overcome this challenge.

  • We also observed overfitting in the training dataset for initial values of K, where the model started memorizing the data points. This occurs because the closest point to any training data point is itself. Hence the prediction is always accurate with K=1. The model performance starts decreasing first for any value greater than K, reaches a minimum, and then starts increasing. I overcame this challenge by plotting the accuracy vs K graph for different values of the (K)NN model. Then picked the top three values with highest accuracy in the validation set.

  • From the research question perspective, one of the challenges related to data is that data is mainly related to the demography of North America and a few Regions of Europe. As we know there can be variations in observed medical conditions for people across continents, due to factors like environment, body type, heat tolerance, and food habits. It will be challenging to extend this model across the globe. Especially in India, where lifestyle and environmental conditions are different from North America/Europe. To overcome this challenge, I would require datasets that have regional demography information as well, as it would help me do an extended comparative study.

  • The size of the dataset is only around 1000, which makes it difficult for the algorithm to understand the important features as well. Especially when trying to understand feature correlation using EDA.

9. Answering the Research Questions.¶

Research Answers:¶

  1. Given the subset of 13 independent variables of the dataset, can we accurately predict the presence or absence of a heart condition for a patient?

Answer: Yes, we were able to build a KNN classification model using 11 out of 14 features that predicts the presence or absence of heart condition with 87.3% accuracy.

  1. What is the highest recall score that we can achieve for this classification problem?

Answer: The recall score that we achieved for this model was 90.8%. This was the performance parameter that was most important for our model as we did not want a high rate of false negatives.

  1. What are the top 3 independent variables (bodily conditions/readings) that have a strong direct or inverse correlation with the "target" variable?

  • slope: Number of major vessels (0-3) colored by fluoroscopy

Numerical:

Risks, Consequences, and Advantages of Applying Model to Unseen Data¶

Risk: Since the model has been trained on people's health data from a specific region in the world (North America, Europe). If applied to the demography of different regions, the risk is that the model might not generalize well to the environmental and lifestyle changes that impact people in different regions of the world. Also, the challenge related to the small size of the dataset has the potential to cause data selection bias, which can lead to erroneous prediction when working with unseen data.

Consequences of Wrong Prediction: Since the model is trying to predict the presence or absence of heart condition. The consequences of wrong prediction can be fatal if only the model is relied upon for the assessment of the heart condition. The model is not meant to be the sole predictor but to be used in supplement to the doctor's analysis. The worst-case scenario for this model is when the model does a false negative prediction. That is, NOT predicting HEART CONDITION (disease) when in reality, the person has a HEART CONDITION.

Advantages of the Model: The advantage of the model is that it can help in the early diagnosis of the patient and supplement the doctors' diagnosis. As mentioned before as well, the model should not be used as a standalone, but when used with other clinical diagnosis processes, it can help speed up the early diagnosis and help preventive action to be started as soon as possible when the results of other diagnoses get reported. Additionally, when the model is right, it can ascertain the doctor's diagnosis and help in the disease analysis over a while, within a specific demography.

Negative and Positive Societal Impacts:¶

Positives: Given that the model predicts accurately and performs as per expectation - it can be used in the early diagnosis of heart conditions in medical patients. This can help in a quick start for the preventive or recovery treatment of the person. Also, these kinds of models can further help in the acceptance of real-life applied data science models in day-to-day medical practice. If the model succeeds, it can be customized for each demographic region as well as extended to the diagnosis of other diseases as well.

Negatives: Over-reliance or sole dependence on models like these can lead to a wrong diagnosis that can be fatal for patients. This eventually can lead to the negativity/rejection of real-life applied data science in the field of medical diagnosis. As stated and stressed multiple times, these models MUST be used as a supplement to a doctor's diagnosis and NOT USED as standalone predictors.
